His oldest son to learning gave his hours

exalting his unclouded powers , His oldest son to learning gave his hours ; By philosophic virtue firmly armed , By moral beauty was Eugenio charmed ; Unaided by high hopes or coward fear , All for itself to him was virtue dear ; Worthy the scale he held in nature's plan , Approved by reason , and becoming man
Worthy the scale he held in nature's plan , Approved by reason , and becoming
no stern decree could flow from heaven
His gentle nature , stranger to offence , Treated the vicious with benevolence
through his actions though they sweetly shone , Those virtues
His knowledge would by patient labour earn , Nor ever deemed himself too wise to learn
of pain and prospect of reward
Such were the sons who won each tender part , Each anxious feeling of Philario's heart , His happiest hours
Thy deeds are wisdom , and thy trust is God , Then who so fit to mark a dubious road

the mariner who near the shore
the dangers over , When sad reverse
To morrow , ever the orb serene of night
him defined , Heaven's mercy with its justice
And thus the intermediate time deceives
the season crowned with Flora's rose
health's full sense and fancy's vivid eye
they leave their parent and their home , And now most pleased they see Alcestes' dome
seemed the sovereign of the vale below
Mid rocks and groves it rose in stately show
Its streams collecting , gathering still new force
the genius of his native place
With hastened step , Philario's sons he meets , And thus in accents mild their coming greets , Welcome young friends
From dignity serene , and mild benevolence , These words mix awe with gentle confidence
In decent order all the household
the blessing of their master's prayer
the blessing of their master's prayer
the hours of eve that yet remain
the harmless jest , or storey's course , Instruction
the sage possessed ; Nor aught escaped them as they took their way , Passing along to where their chambers lay
O deign , they said , the mystery to relate , And why those figures meet such different fate
One narrow path to a bright mansion led , Along the landscape , over the canvas spread ; Three figures pass it with a different fate
At early matins they with joy attend , And anxious wait
At early matins they with joy attend , And anxious wait the coming of their friend
them her salubrious treat , And bread and fruits their wholesome meal complete , Enraptured of the pictures now they speak , And for their meaning to Alcestes seek
O deign , they said , the mystery to relate , And why those figures meet such different fate
the pieces which they wish to read
This said , a scroll of parchment next he shows , And thus proceeds its legend to disclose
those whose dubious worth high fortune crowned
